
MySQL commands can be grouped into categories like Database Management (CREATE, DROP, USE), 
Table Management (CREATE TABLE, ALTER, DROP), Data Manipulation (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, SELECT),
and User/Privilege Management (CREATE USER, GRANT, REVOKE). Below is a structured list of the most important MySQL commands you‚Äôll use.


üìå Core MySQL Commands
üîπ Database Management
‚Ä¢	CREATE DATABASE dbname; ‚Üí Create a new database
‚Ä¢	SHOW DATABASES;         ‚Üí List all databases
‚Ä¢	USE dbname;             ‚Üí Switch to a database/select database
‚Ä¢	DROP DATABASE dbname;   ‚Üí Delete a database
> SYSTEM CLS;             ‚Üí Clear Screen

üîπ Table Management
‚Ä¢	CREATE TABLE table_name (...);                    ‚Üí Create a new table
‚Ä¢	SHOW TABLES;                                      ‚Üí List tables in the current database
‚Ä¢	DESCRIBE table_name;                              ‚Üí Show table structure
‚Ä¢	ALTER TABLE table_name ADD column_name datatype;  ‚Üí Add a new column
‚Ä¢	ALTER TABLE table_name DROP column_name;          ‚Üí Remove a column
‚Ä¢	DROP TABLE table_name;                            ‚Üí Delete a table

üîπ Data Manipulation (DML)
‚Ä¢	INSERT INTO table_name VALUES (...);                ‚Üí Insert new data
‚Ä¢	SELECT * FROM table_name;                           ‚Üí Retrieve data
‚Ä¢	UPDATE table_name SET column=value WHERE condition; ‚Üí Update existing data
‚Ä¢	DELETE FROM table_name WHERE condition;             ‚Üí Delete data

üîπ Data Definition (DDL)
‚Ä¢	CREATE INDEX idx_name ON table_name(column);        ‚Üí Create an index
‚Ä¢	DROP INDEX idx_name ON table_name;                  ‚Üí Remove an index

üîπ User & Privilege Management
‚Ä¢	CREATE USER 'username'@'host' IDENTIFIED BY 'password';   ‚Üí Create a new user
‚Ä¢	GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON dbname.* TO 'username'@'host';    ‚Üí Grant permissions
‚Ä¢	REVOKE ALL PRIVILEGES ON dbname.* FROM 'username'@'host'; ‚Üí Remove permissions
‚Ä¢	DROP USER 'username'@'host'; ‚Üí Delete a user

üîπ MySQL Client Commands (special commands inside mysql> prompt)
‚Ä¢	\h ‚Üí Help (list all commands)
‚Ä¢	\u dbname   ‚Üí Switch database
‚Ä¢	\q          ‚Üí Quit MySQL client
‚Ä¢	\c          ‚Üí Clear current input
‚Ä¢	\d          ‚Üí Set statement delimiter
‚Ä¢	\G          ‚Üí Display query results vertically

üìä Comparison Table of Key Command Categories

1.Database Management	
CREATE DATABASE, USE, DROP	Manage databases

2.Table Management	
CREATE TABLE, ALTER, DROP	Define and modify tables

3.Data Manipulation	
INSERT, SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE	Work with data

4.User Management
CREATE USER, GRANT, REVOKE, DROP	Control access

5.Client Commands
\h, \q, \c, \d, \G	MySQL shell operations


1Ô∏è‚É£ Delete (DROP) a single column from a table
If you want to remove the column itself from the table structure:
ALTER TABLE table_name
DROP COLUMN column_name;

2Ô∏è‚É£ Delete data from a single column (keep the column)
If you want to clear values in a column but keep the column:
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = NULL;

3Ô∏è‚É£ Delete data from a column with condition
Delete values only for specific rows:
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = NULL
WHERE condition;

4Ô∏è‚É£ Delete row(s) based on column value
If you want to delete entire rows based on a column:
DELETE FROM table_name
WHERE column_name = value;

5. modify column name
Use RENAME COLUMN (simplest and safest):
ALTER TABLE table_name
RENAME COLUMN old_column_name TO new_column_name;

6. Modify column name + datatype together
ALTER TABLE users
CHANGE age user_age INT NOT NULL;




